Yes, in C, you can use type casting (force type conversion) to convert a struct variable from one type to another. However, it is important to note that this technique should be used with caution, as it can lead to undefined behavior if the memory layout or field types of the structs are not compatible.

Here's an example:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <string.h>

typedef struct {
    char name[50];
    int age;
} Person;

typedef struct {
    char fullName[50];
    int years;
} Employee;

int main() {
    Person person;
    strcpy(person.name, "John Doe");
    person.age = 30;

    // Type cast Person to Employee
    Employee* employee = (Employee*) &person;

    printf("Person: %s, %d years old\n", person.name, person.age);
    printf("Employee: %s, %d years\n", employee->fullName, employee->years);

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, we first create a `Person` struct and assign values to its fields. Then, we use a type cast `(Employee*)` to convert the `person` struct variable to an `Employee*` (pointer to `Employee` type). However, note that the memory layout and field types of `Person` and `Employee` are not necessarily compatible, so this conversion may not produce the desired results or may even lead to undefined behavior.

It is generally recommended to use explicit mapping (manually copying field values) or redesign the structs to have compatible field names and types rather than relying on force type conversion.

