In Linux, timers are typically implemented using the `timerfd` interface. The timers created using `timerfd` are based on file descriptors rather than explicit expiry times.

With `timerfd`, you can set the expiry time for a timer by using the `timerfd_settime()` function. Here's an example:

```c
#include <stdio.h>
#include <unistd.h>
#include <sys/timerfd.h>

int main() {
    int fd = timerfd_create(CLOCK_MONOTONIC, 0);

    struct itimerspec new_timer;
    new_timer.it_value.tv_sec = 2;              // Initial expiration time in seconds
    new_timer.it_value.tv_nsec = 0;             // Initial expiration time in nanoseconds
    new_timer.it_interval.tv_sec = 1;           // Interval between expiration times in seconds
    new_timer.it_interval.tv_nsec = 0;          // Interval between expiration times in nanoseconds

    timerfd_settime(fd, 0, &new_timer, NULL);

    // Wait for timer expiration
    uint64_t expirations;
    read(fd, &expirations, sizeof(expirations));

    printf("Timer expired!\n");

    close(fd);

    return 0;
}
```

In this example, we create a timer using `timerfd_create()`. We then set the expiration time and interval for the timer using the `new_timer` struct and the `timerfd_settime()` function. 

The `it_value` field of `new_timer` specifies the initial expiration time, and the `it_interval` field specifies the interval between expiration times. 

We then use the `read()` function to wait for the timer expiration. Once the timer expires, the `printf()` statement will be executed.

After using the timer, make sure to close the file descriptor with `close()`.

So, while Linux timers do not have a direct concept of expiry time, timers created with `timerfd` can be configured with an initial expiry time and an interval between expiration times.
